That line is now being blurred. When officers are pressured to prove loyalty, when neutrality is treated as suspicion, and when dissent is framed as betrayal, the military stops being a professional force and starts becoming a political instrument.
The U.S. military has long been different. It has operated on the idea that it answers to the Constitution, not to a president‚Äôs ego or a political movement.

Stalinism wasn‚Äôt only about secret police and show trials. At its core, it was about loyalty replacing competence. The military was purged of experienced leaders who were seen as insufficiently obedient, not ineffective.
